      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "March 25, 1875\n\nI have been observing the native population with great interest, and I must confess that their inherent limitations are both fascinating and distressing. Their primitive ignorance is not merely a lack of knowledge, but a fundamental dearth of intellectual and moral fibre. They are a people prone to passion and impulse, governed more by their base instincts than by reason or reflection. Theirs is a temperament better suited to the simple, instinctual life of the savannah, rather than the complex, rational existence of the civilized world. It is little wonder, then, that their societies are so often marked by chaos and disorder, their decisions guided more by superstition and whim than by a rational consideration of the greater good. As for their capacity for self-governance, I fear it is a myth, a sentimental conceit that must be dispelled by the firm hand of British authority. We are not merely their rulers, but their saviours, guiding them towards a brighter future that they are incapable of achieving on their own.",
